<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="truth-tables">
  <title>Truth Tables</title>

  <p>
    A truth table shows all possible truth values of a compound statement.
    Each row represents one possible combination of truth values for the variables.
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Complete the truth table for the compound proposition:

      <me>
        (p \rightarrow q) \land (\neg q)
      </me>

      Follow these steps:
      <ol>
        <li>Compute <m>p \rightarrow q</m></li>
        <li>Compute <m>\neg q</m></li>
        <li>Combine results using <m>\land</m></li>
      </ol>

      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>p</m></cell>
          <cell><m>q</m></cell>
          <cell><m>p \rightarrow q</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\neg q</m></cell>
          <cell><m>(p \rightarrow q) \land (\neg q)</m></cell>
        </row>

        <row>
          <cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
        </row>

        <row>
          <cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
        </row>

        <row>
          <cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
        </row>

        <row>
          <cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      The final column evaluates to: F, T, F, F  
      (so the statement is only true in the second row)
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Construct truth tables for the following expressions and determine whether they are logically equivalent:

      <ol type="a">
        <li><m>\neg (p \lor q)</m></li>
        <li><m>(\neg p \land \neg q)</m></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      Yes, they are logically equivalent (De Morgan’s Law).
    </solution>
  </exercise>
</section>